column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1630 ON APRIL 6, 1994, AN FRA INSPECTOR REPORTED TANK CAR GATX 25612, RESIDUE: LAST CONTAINED AMMONIA, ANHYDROUS, 2.2, UN1005, RQ, LEAKING. THE TANK CAR HAD NOT BEEN PULLED FROM THE CONSIGNEES FACILITY WHERE IT HAD BEEN PULLED. THE CONSIGNEE DECLINED TO TAKE ANY CORRECTIVE ACTION. CHEMTREC WAS CALLED TO REQUEST ASSISTANCE FROM THE BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES INSPECTOR HEADQUARTERED IN OMAHA, NEBRASKA. THE BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES INSPECTOR RESPONDED AND DETERMINED THAT THE LEAKAGE WAS COMING FROM BETWEEN THE BASE OF THE A-END LIQUID VALVE AND THE MANWAY COVER PLATE. AFTER THE LEAK WAS STOPPED BY TIGHTENING THE NUTS SECURING THE VALVE, THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT BACK TO THE LOADING FACILITY.

column168: VEHICLE 1 SOUTHBOUND ON ST. FRANCIS APPROACHING SIGNAL LIGHT AT INTERSECTION WITH ALAMO STREET.  OTHER TRAFFIC HAD STOPPED FOR RED SIGNAL LIGHT IN ALL THREE LANES.  VEHICLE 1 LEFT ROADWAY TO THE RIGHT TO AVOID IMPACTING OTHER TRAFFIC.  VEHICLE 1 OVERTURNED THREE QUARTERS OF A ROLL COMING TO A REST ON ITS LEFT SIDE.  DURING THE THREE QUARTER ROLL THE DOME LID IMPACTED THE PAVEMENT AND CAUSED DAMAGE TO THE SEAL BETWEEN THE DOME LID AND THE CARGO TANK.  THIS MINOR DAMAGE DID ALLOW FUEL TO LEAK FROM THAT AREA AS THE VEHICLE WAS AT FINAL REST ON ITS LEFT SIDE.  THE NEW MEXICO STATE POLICE AND ITS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE PERSONNEL, THE SANTA FE FIRE DEPARTMENT, THE SANTA FE POLICE AND ITS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE PERSONNEL, THE D.O.T., THE NEW MEXICO HIGHWAY DEPARTMENT, AND THE SANTA FE PUBLIC WORKS PERSONNEL ALL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE CRUSHING FINES USED TO CONTAIN THE SPILL IS NOW BEING LAB TESTED.  IF APPLICABLE, THE WASTE WILL BE DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO ALL LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.

column168: THE SHIPMENT INVOLVED IN THE SPILL CONSISTED OF 72 (15) GALLON POLYETHYLENE DRUMS.  THE DRUMS WERE BANDED (6) EACH TO A WORD PALLET. LATE IN THE EVENING ON 4/12/94 N & M TRANSFER DOCK PERSONNEL HAD REMOVED THE SKIDS OF THESE DRUMS FROM THE ORIGINAL PICK UP TRAILER.  THE DRUMS WERE PLACED ON THE DOCK FOR LOADING AT A LATER TIME.  AT 01:40AM ON WEDNESDAY A DOCKMAN BEGIN LOADING THESE SKIDS ON TO A TRAILER.  AFTER LOADING THE LAST SKID THE DOCKMAN BECAME AWARE OF AN ODOR AND A MIST COMING FROM THE TRAILER.  IN A VERY SHORT WHILE THE VAPORS AND ODOR BECAME QUITE STRONG.  I WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL AT 02:00 A.M.  AFTER CHECKING THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE WE AGREED TO NOTIFY CHEM-TREC WHICH WAS LISTED ON THE SHIPPING PAPER AT THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER.  CHEMTREC, THEN, IN TURN, NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0300 AM THE SHIPPER CALLED OUT TERMINAL AND ADVISED OUR PERSONNEL TO ENTER THE TRAILER WITH NEGATIVE PRESSURE RESPIRATORS AND LOCATED THE LEAKING CONTAINER.  THEY ADIVSED US THAT AFTER WE LOCATE THE LEAKING CONTAINER WE SHOULD PLACE IT IN A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE N&M FOREMAN COULD NOT LOCATE THE DRUM BECAUSE EACH PALLET CONTAINED DRUMS THAT WERE BANDED TOGETHER, MAKING IT HARD TO DETERMINE WHICH DRUM WAS THE LIGHTEST AS A RESULT OF THE LEAKAGE.  BY 3:30AM THE LEAKING DRUM HAD BEEN LOCATED.  IT WAS FOUND TO HAVE CONTAINED A PIN HOLE LEAK ON THE BOTTOM OUTSIDE RING, WHICH WE BELIEVED WAS CAUSED BY A NAIL PORTRUDING FROM THE PALLET THAT THE SHIPPER HAD LOCATED IT ON. THE SPILLAGE INVOLVED THE COMPLETE LOSS OF 15 GALLONS OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID FROM ONE POLYETHYLENE DRUM.  IT IS MY RECOMMENDATION THAT ALL POLYETHYLENE DRUM HAVE RE-INFORCED BOTTOMS SO THAT ALL PORTRUDING OBJECTS, SUCH AS NAILS, AND FLARED TRAILER WALLS, CANNOT PENETRATE AND CAUSE SPILLAGE.  ALL SPILL AREAS IN THE TRAILER AND GROUND LEVEL WERE NEUTRALIZED AND WASHED CLEAN WITH WATER.

THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (REPORT #235062) AND THE LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE DEPARTMENTS WERE NOTIFIED.  THE WASTE WAS TRANSFERRED FROM THE DUMP TRAILER INTO VACUUM BOXES AND ROUTE ON TO THE DESIGNATED DISPOSAL FACILITY (CONSIGNEE).  THE SPILL AREA WAS REMEDIATED AND THE SCENE WAS CLEARED BY THE DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION.  THE REMEDIATION OF THE SPILL AREA RESULTED IN FOUR (4) FIFTY FIVE (55) GALLON DRUMS OF PLASTIC FLOOR DRY AND PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT.  THIS MATERIAL WILL BE DISPOSED OF AT A PERMITTED TSD FACILITY.  THIS WAS THE FIRST LOAD WPI TRANSPORTATION INC., HAD HAULED FOR THE SHIPPER AND NO SEPERATION OF THE MATERIAL WAS EXPECTED. FUTURE SHIPMENTS OF THIS WASTE WILL BE TRANSPORTED USING WATER TIGHT ROLL-OFF BOXED AND OR THE SHIPPER WILL ENSURE THAT THE WASTE MATERIAL WILL BE COMPLETELY DRIED BEFORE OFFERING FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column168: ON APRIL 8, 1994 ARRANGEMENTS WERE FINALIZED BETWEEN ARCO PIPE LINE COMPANY(APL) AND USPCI TREATMENT AND RECOVERY SERVICES (USPCI) FOR THE TRANSPORATION AND DISPOSAL OF APPROXIMATELY 2300 GALLONS OF A METHANOL\WATER MIXTURE.  DUE TO EXTREMELY COLD TEMPERATURE, THE METHANOL\WATER MIXTURE HAD PREVIOUSLY BEEN USED TO HYDROSTATIC TEST A NEW RIVER CROSSING NEAR OSAWATOMIE, KANSAS.  AT 1445 HOURS ON APRIL 8, 1994, IT WAS BROUGHT TO OUR ATTENTION THAT THE METHANOL\WATER MIXTURE MAY HAVE BEEN DISCHARGED TO THE SOIL.  AFTER CONTACTING SEVERAL INDIVIDUALS WHO WERE AT THE TRANSFER SITE, IT WAS REVEALED THAT AN INDENTATION TO THE SOIL WAS FOUND WHERE THE MIXTURE HAD IMPACTED THE SOIL.  BASED UPON THIS INFORMATION, THE ASSUMPTION WAS MADE THAT A DISCHARGE HAD OCCURRED.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS TELEPHONICALLY NOTIFIED AT 1616 HOURS ON APRIL 8, 1994.  THE KANSAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONEMENT WAS NOTIFIED AT 1630 HOURS ON APRIL 8, 1994.

column168: CAPE CANAVERAL TRUCK & BUS HAS AN ABOVE GROUND TANK.  THE CONSIGNEE LOCATION EMPLOYEE IS SUPPOSE TO STICK THE TANKS; HOWEVER, THE CONSIGNEE EMPLOYEE TOLD OUR DRIVER TO GO AHEAD AND DELIVER THE LOAD, BECAUSE THEY WERE OUT OF PRODUCT. THE TANK IS A 10,000 GALLON TANK AND THEY HAD ORDERED 7,500 GALLONS SO HE STATED THERE WOULD BE NO PROBLEM WITH THE PRODUCT FITTING.  IT WAS DARK WHEN OUR DRIVER DELIVERED THIS LOAD AND DID NOT REALIZE THE TANK HAD OVERFILLED UNTIL HE SAW THE PRODUCT RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TANK.  THE CONSIGNEE TOOK FULL RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE SPILL AND CLEANED IT UP.  THE 100 GALLON SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO THE OVERFILL RETENTION AREA.  THERE WAS NO SOIL CONTAMINATION.

A CARGO TANK WAS DISPATCHED BY CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. TO TEXAS INSTRUMENTS LOCATED AT 34 FOREST STREET IN ATTLEBORO, MA IN ORDER TO PICK UP A LOAD OF WASTE FERRIS CHLORIDE SOLUTION.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE LOADING FACILITY DRIVER OF THE CARGO TANK ALONG WITH PERSONNEL FROM TEXAS INSTRUMENTS ("TI") INITIATED ALL THE REQUIRED STEPS TO PREPARE THE MATERIAL FOR TRANSFER, THE VALVE TO THE STORAGE TANK WAS COMPLETION OF THE TRANSFER, THE VALVE TO THE STORAGE TANK WAS CLOSED AND WATER WAS FLUSHED THE SYSTEM OF ANY RESIDUAL PRODUCT.  AFTER THIS OPERATION WAS COMPLETE, THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO DISCONNECT THE TRANSFER HOSE FROM THE TANK AND PREPARE TO SECURE THE HOSES TO HIS VEHICLE.  AS HE REMOVED THE HOSE, RESIDUAL MATERIAL IN THE TRANSFER HOSE WAS RELEASED INTO A FULLY CONTAINED CONCRETE LOADING PAD.  IN ADDITION, THE DRIVER WAS SPLASHED WITH THIS MATERIAL AND IMMEDIATELY WENT TO A SAFETY SHOWER TO FLUSH ANY PRODUCT OFF HIS SKIN AND CLOTHING.  HE THEN CHANGED CLOTHES AND WAS SEEN BY ON-SITE MEDICAL PERSONNEL WHO IDENTIFIED NO INJURIES AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT. TI THEN INITIATED STEPS NECESSARY TO PUMP THE FREE LIQUID THAT WAS RELEASED INTO THE CARGO TANK AND TO CONTAINERIZE ALL RESIDUAL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS (I.E. ABSORBENT MATERIAL) IN A SUITABLE CONTAINER THAT WILL BE SENT OFF-SITE TO A FULLY LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY FOR DISPOSAL.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, THE DRIVER HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED IN THE PROPER PROCEDURES THAT MUST BE FOLLOWED WHEN DISCONNECTING TRANSFER HOSES USED IN ANY PUMPING OPERATIONS.  IN ADDITION, A MEANS OF SECONDARY CONTAINMENT (I.E. AN OPEN TOP DRUM) WILL BE AVAILABLE TO CAPTURE ANY RESIDUAL LIQUID REMAINING IN THE TRANSFER HOSE.

FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRY AND OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM FOR CONTINUING SHIPMENT TO SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC.  IN ADDITION, APPROXIMATELY 250 POUNDS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS PLACED INTO A 55 GALLON DRUM AND WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGH CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC. LOCATED AT 2900 BROADWAY IN CLEVELAND, OH.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

column168: DOCK MAN HAD JUST FINISHED PLACING CARTON ON THE REAR OF AN OUTBOUND TRAILER WHEN HE NOTICED THE CARTON WAS LEAKING. THE IMPACT CAUSED ONE OF THE GLASS JUGS TO BREAK.  CARTON TRANSFERRED TO OS & D FOR FURTHER HANDLING.  DOCK PERSONNERL MUST EXERCISE MORE CONTROL AND CAUTION WHEN LOADING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS IN GLASS CONTAINERS.

column168: DRIVER LOADED BOTH GASOLINE AND DIESEL FUEL ON THE TRUCK.  WHILE UNLOADING THE GASOLINE PORTION OF THE LOAD, HE NOTICED A GROUP OF YOUND KIDS LOITERING AROUND THE SIDE OF THE SERVICE STATION HE WAS UNLOADING AT.  HE FINISHED UNLOADING THE GASOLINE.  IN ORDER TO UNLOAD THE DIESEL FUEL HE HAD TO RE POSITION THE TRUCK BECAUSE IT WAS TOO FAR AWAY FROM THE UNLOADING DROP OF THE TANK TO SAFELY REACH WITH THE HOSES HE HAD ON THE TRUCK.  HE CLOSED THE INTERNAL SAFETY VALVES, PUT THE HOSES HE USED TO UNLOAD THE GASOLINE INTO THE HOSE RACK AND PROCEEDED BACK INTO THE CAB OF THE TRUCK.  HE MOVED THE TRUCK INTO POSITION TO UNLOAD THE DIESEL FUEL. HE GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK AND WENT AROUND THE DISCHARGE SIDE OF THE TRUCK WHERE HE NOTICED PRODUCT COMING OUT OF THE DISCHARGE LINE OF THE #4 COMPARTMENT. AT THAT TIME HE ALSO NOTICED ONE OF THE THE YOUNG KIDS THAT HAD BEEN LOITERING WAS NOW RUNNING FROM THE BACK OF THE TRUCK.  HE SHUT THE DISCHARGE HANDLE AND USED SORBENT TO CLEAN THE DIESEL OFF OF THE PAVEMENT AND ASPHALT.  THE PRODUCT THAT SPILLED WAS FROM THE #4 COCMPARTMENT WET LINE- APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS.

THE ENTIRE AMOUNT OF THE SPILL WENT INTO THE RECOVERY TANK AND WAS RECOVERED.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0730 ON APRIL 27, 1994, A SHIPMENT OF WASTE BEING IMPORTED FROM CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT DE MEXICO, KM 14.5, CARRETERA ESCENICA, TIJUANA B.C., MEXICO ARRIVED AT CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT, INC. ("CWM"), 2301 WEST BROADWAY ROAD, PHOENIX, ARIZONA, WHICH IS PERMITTED FOR THE STORAGE OF HAZARDOUS WASTE IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE ARIZONA HAZARDOUS WASTE MANAGEMENT ACT, AZT050010180. CWM, 1704 WEST FIRST STREET, AZUSA, CALIFORNIA WAS THE IMPORTER OR RECORD. THE WASTE WAS SHIPPED ON A UNIFORM HAZARDOUS WASTE A MANIFEST, DOCUMENT NUMBER 00735. CHEMICAL DISPOSAL WAS THE TRANSPORTER, AZT050010008. AS THE VEHICLE (TRACTOR TRAILER) WAS BEING UNLOADED ONE OF THE FORKS OF THE FACILITY FORKLIFT PUNCTURED THE BOTTOM OF A PLASTIC WOVEN BAG CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE (PROPER SHIPPING NAME: "RQ" WASTE ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE SOLID, N.O.S. (LEAD)). THE WASTE WAS CONSIDERED HAZARDOUS DUE TO THE TOXICITY CHARACTERISTIC FOR LEAD (D008). THE FORK STRUCK THE CONTAINER DUE TO THE FAILURE OF THE WOODEN PALLET UPON WHICH THE CONTAINER HAD BEEN PLACED. THE MIDDLE PORTION OF THE PALLET, WHICH WAS NOT VISIBLE FROM THE ENTRY POINT OF THE FORKLIFT, HAD COLLAPSED CAUSING THE BOTTOM SECTION OF THE CONTAINER TO PROTRUDE. WHEN THE FORKS WERE PLACED UNDER THE FRONT PORTION OF THE PALLET AND EXTENDED FORWARD THE CONTAINER WAS PUNCTURED. THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR CEASED MOVEMENT OF THE CONTAINER AS SOON AS HE REALIZED THAT ITS INTEGRITY HAD BEEN BREACHED. FACILITY PERSONNEL THEN CONTACTED THEIR SUPERVISOR WHO IN TURN CONTACTED THE EMERGENCY COORDINATOR. IN ORDER TO ADDRESS THE RELEASE, THE CONTAINER, INCLUDING THE DAMAGED PALLET, WERE PLACED ON PLASTIC SHEETING OUTSIDE OF THE VEHICLE AND THE SPILL AREA. APPROXIMATELY TWO (2) POUNDS OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED ONTO THE FLOORING OF THE VEHICLE AND AN EQUAL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED INTO THE FACILITY GRAVELED YARD AT THE REAR OF THE VEHICLE. THE MATERIAL CONTAINED LESS THAN 1% LEAD, THEREFORE A REPORTABLE QUANTITY OF MATERIAL WAS NOT RELEASED. THE MATERIAL RELEASED ONTO THE VEHICLE FLOORING WAS COLLECTED AND PLACED IN A PLASTIC BAG WHICH WAS THEN PLACED IN A STEEL 55-GALLON DRUM. THE VEHICLE FLOORING WAS DECONTAMINATED WITH A DETERGENT SOLUTION. THE SOLUTION WAS ABSORBED WITH PAPER TOWELING. THE FORKS OF THE FORKLIFT WERE DECONTAMINATED IN A SIMILAR MANNER. ALL TOWELING WAS PLACED IN A PLASTIC BAG AND STEEL DRUM ALONG WITH THE RELEASED MATERIAL. THE VEHICLE WAS THEN MOVED TO ALLOW THE FACILITY TO ADDRESS THE MATERIAL RELEASED ON THE GRAVELED AREA. THE VEHICLE AND FORKLIFT DECONTAMINATION WAS COMPLETED BY 09:30. ALL VISIBILY AFFECTED AREAS OF GRAVEL AND SOIL WERE COLLECTED. IN TOTAL APPROXIMATELY TWENTY (20) POUNDS OF GRAVEL AND SOIL WERE EXCAVATED. THE MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN A PLASTIC BAG WHICH WAS THEN PLACED IN A STEEL 55-GALLON DRUM. THE AFFECTED AREA MEASURED APPROXIMATELY 5 FEET BY 6 FEET. SIXTEEN (16) SOIL SAMPLES WERE COLLECTED FROM THE CLEANED SURFACE OF THE SPILL AREA, ONE SAMPLE FOR EVERY TWO SQUARE FEET

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: TWO 4,000 GALLON TANKS MANIFOLDED TOGETHER. WOULDN'T HOLD ALL OF PRODUCT BECAUSE CUSTOMER OVER-ORDERED ON GASOLINE AND TANKS OVERFILLED. SPILL CLEANED UP BY REDWING PERSONNEL AND BROUGHT TO TAMP TERMINAL FOR DISPOSAL. PUT INTO THREE 55 GALLON DRUMS.

AT 1315 HOURS ON APRIL 19TH IN NIAGARA YARD, ENGINEER D. STEELE NOTICED A SPRAY FROM THE MANWAY OF HOKX 8261. HE STOPPED ALL MOVEMENT AND THE  CREW OBSERVED THE CAR FOR TEN MINUTES. NO ADDITIONAL PRODUCT ESCAPED WHILE THE CAR WAS AT REST. THEY CAREFULLY ISOLATED THE CAR AT THE SHOP AND ON OCCIDENTAL E.R. TEAM INVESTIGATED. THE TEAM FOUND A "CRIMPED" MANWAY COVER GASKET AND REPLACED IT. TANK CAR RETURNED TO TRANSPORTATION AT 1430 HOURS.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: MANWAY GASKET HAD FOREIGN MATERIAL APPLIED TO THE GASKET CAUSING AN INADEQUATE SEAL AROUND THE MANWAY OPENING. MANWAY GASKET WAS REPLACED, CAR DECONTAMINATED AND RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

TY-GARD BRACING MATERIAL WAS IMPROPERLY APPLIED RESULTING IN 1 55-GALLON DRUM TO FALL FROM THE TOP LAYER OF A DOUBLE LAYER LOAD. DRUM WAS PUNCTURED ON THE LOWER ROLL-RING OF THE DRUM RELEASING 20 GALLONS OF PRODUCT. TEMPORARY REPAIRS WERE MADE TO THE DRUM AND THEN TRANSFERRED INTO A NEW DRUM ALONG WITH TWO OTHER DAMAGED BUT NON LEAKING DRUMS. CONTAINER WAS TRANSLOADED INTO APLS 283834 AND RELEASED TO DESTINATION. CONTAMINATED CONTAINER WAS RELEASED TO AMERICAN PRESIDENT LINES FOR REDECKING AND DECONTAMINATION.

WAREHOUSE EMPLOYEE WAS ATTEMPTING TO PLACE A 55 GALLON DRUM ON A SKID BY HIMSELF WHEN THE DRUM FELL OFF THE SKID, HITTING THE SIDE OF THE SKID AND THE DRUM CRACKED OPEN ON ITS SIDE.  THE WAREHOUSE EMPLOYEE DID GET SOME SULFURIC ACID ON HIMSELF WHICH WAS WASHED OFF.  HE WAS SENT TO THE OCCUPATIONAL MEDICAL CLINIC, 3033 SOUTH 27TH STREET, MILWAUKEE, WI, WHERE HE WAS TOLD TO GO HOME AND TAKE A LONG SHOWER.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: FLT 1263 DEPARTED ROCHESTER NY ENROUTE TO MEMPHIS TN.  SHORTLY AFTER DEPARTURE, THE CREW SMELLED A STRONG SULPHUR ODOR.  CREW DECLARED AN EMERGENCY AND DIVERTED TO CLEVELAND HOPKINS AIRPORT.  ONCE REALIZING THEY MAY HAVE A POTENTIALLY TOXIC INHALATION HAZARD, THE CREW WENT ON OXYGEN. UPON ARRIVAL AT CLEVELAND, THEY TAXIED THE AIRCRAFT TO THE FEDERAL EXPRESS RAMP WHERE CLEVELAND AIRPORT'S CRASH FIRE RESCUE TEAM WAS AWAITING THEIR ARRIVAL.  THIS CREW DEBRIEFED THE CREW AND STARTED REVIEWING THE DANGEROUS GOODS FLT MANIFESTS.  ADDITIONALLY, THEY WERE GATHERING INFORMATION ABOUT THE HAZARDS.  SOME 2 1/2 HOURS LATER, THEY BOARD THE AIRCRAFT.  WITHIN A SHORT AMOUNT OF TIME, THEY HAD DETERMINED THAT THE ODOR WAS NOT COMING FROM THE AIRCRAFT'S DANGEROUS GOODS CONTAINER.  THE CRASH FIRE RESCUE TEAM WAS UNLOADED CHECKING INSIDE EACH OF THE AIRCRAFT'S FREIGHT CONTAINERS. IN POSITION 7, THE PROBLEM PACKAGE WAS LOCATED.  THE PACKAGE WAS BUTYL SULFIDE WHICH IS NOT LISTED BY NAME AS A DANGEROUS GOOD.  ADDITIONALLY THE MSDS WAS EVENTUALLY OBTAINED WHICH DID NOT IDENTIFY ANY HAZARD WHICH WOULD DIRECTLY CLASSIFY THE MATERIAL AS A DANGEROUS GOOD.  THE MSDS DID IDENTIFY THE MATERIAL AS A CONT "STINCH" EMITTING MATERIAL.  EASTMAN DID NOT REGULATE THIS MATERIAL AS A DANGEROUS GOOD.  HOWEVER, CHEMICAL PRODUCT LINE WAS PURCHASED 1/1/94 BY FISHER SCIENTIFIC WHICH ARE THE CURRENT OWNERS OF ALL EASTMAN CHEMICAL PRODUCTS.  I SPOKE TO FISHER SCIENTIFIC (WHO PROVIDED THE MSDS IN THE FIRST PLACE), WHO STATED THAT AS FAR AS THEY ARE CONCERNED, FUTURE SHIPMENTS WOULD BE SHIPPED AS "OTHER REGULATED SUBSTANCE LIQUID, NOS".  AFTER REVIEWING THIS INCIDENT AND TALKING WITH THE CREW AND EMPLOYEES WHO CONTAINED THE SPILL, I AGREE THIS SHOULD BE SENT AS A REGULATED SUBSTANCE LIQUID, NOS.  THE SMELL IS REPORTED TO BE SO STRONG THAT IT IS NAUSEATING AND WOULD AFFECT CREW'S CAPABILITY OF OPERATING THE AIRCRAFT.  WHAT CONCERNS ME MOST IS HOW MANY OTHER "APPARENT" NON-REGULATED MATERIALS COULD ALSO CAUSE THIS PROBLEM.
TOP OF JERRICAN'S LID WAS DEFECTIVE & IT LEAKED A SMALL AMOUNT.  PACKAGE WAS HELD & THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED.

column168: WHILE FILLING DRUMS OF 50% CAUSTIC SODA FROM THE FIRST COMPARTMENT OF A BULK TRUCK, THE FOURTH COMPARTMENT STARTED RELEASING 50% CAUSTIC SODA INTO A CATCH PAN, WHICH SUBSEQUENTLY OVERFLOWED ONTO THE BULK PAD. THE EXTERNAL AND INTERNAL VALVES WERE SHUT, STOPPING THE FLOW. THE STORM DRAIN WAS CLOSED SO THAT NO PRODUCT WAS RELEASED INTO THE ENVIRONMENT. THE EXTERNAL VALVE ON COMPARTMENT #4 WAS PARTIALLY FROZEN WHEN IT ARRIVED. THE OPERATOR ATTEMPTED TO OPEN THIS VALVE TO GET PRODUCT OUT FOR THE DRUM FILL. WHEN HE COULD NOT GET ANY PRODUCT OUT, HE CLOSED THE EXTERNAL VALVE AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE, CLOSED THE INTERNAL VALVE, AND CONNECTED THE HOSE TO COMPARTMENT #1. AS THE TEMPERATURE INCREASED, THE EXTERNAL VALVE ON COMPARTMENT #4 THAWED AND ALLOWED PRODUCT TO COME OUT OF IT. THE INTERNAL VALVE FAILED COMPLETELY. FACTS LEARNED: 1.  50% CAUSTIC SODA FREEZES AT 54 DEGREES F. 2.  TEMPERATURE WAS A FACTOR.  3. THE INTERNAL VALVE FAILED. 4.  THE EXTERNAL VALVE WAS PARTIALLY FROZEN.  5.  TIME/MANPOWER WAS A FACTOR. 6.  ALTHOUGH THE ATTACHED INVENTORY REPORT INDICATES A MAXIMUM LOSS OF 215 LBS., IT IS BELIEVED THAT 100-150 LBS. WERE SPILLED BASED ON: A. VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE AREA  B. 1:1 DILUTION OF CITRIC ACID  C. DRUM FILLING VARIANCES  7.  PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT WAS USED PROPERLY DURING THE FILL AND CLEAN UP, RESULTING IN NO INJURIES TO PERSONNEL. CORRECTIVE ACTIONS: 1.  INTERNAL VALVE TO BE REPAIRED BY 05/04/94.  2. TRAINING ON INCIDENT INVESTIGATION TO BE COMPLETED BY 05/06/94. 3. RECOMMENDED THAT WE PURCHASE A STEAM GENERATOR TO THAW VALVES. 4. PLANT MANAGER TO CHECK TRAILER PM(S) CONCERNING INTERNAL VALVES FOR ADEQUACY BY 05/10/94. 5. TJA FOR UNLOADING BULK CORROSIVES INTO INTO DRUMS TO BE COMPLETED BY 05/30/94. 6. RECOMMENDED THAT THE NEW FACILITY INCLUDE SPECIFIC CONTAINMENT FOR CORROSIVE UNLOADING. JOHN WOODRUM IS RESPONSIBLE FOR THE ABOVE FOLLOW UP WHICH WILL BE COMPLETED BY 05/30/94.

column168: SPILL OCCURED AT APPROXIMATELY 20:00 HOURS ON WEDNESDAY APRIL 6, 1994. SPILL ORIGINATED AT THE UNLEADED REGULAR UST, RAN SOUTH TO "B" STREET, THEN EAST STAYING IN THE GUTTER.  SPILL WAS CONTAINED BY DRIVER, CLAY DUMSMORE, AND SPARKS FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE SPILL WAS REPORTED IMMEDIATELY TO MYSELF AND THE SPARKS FIRE DEPARTMENT. CAPT. FLOCK FROM SPARKS FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS IN CHARGE.  ROGER CLARK, WITH WESTERN ENERGETIX, CONTACTED DISPOSAL CONTROL SERVICE FOR THE SPILL REMEDIATION.  DISPOSAL CONTROL TOOK CUSTODY OF THE RESIDUE AND CLEAN UP MATERIALS AT THE SITE.  DISPOSAL CONTROL ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 20:30.  THE SITE WAS INSPECTED BY ROBERT SACK, WASHOE COUNTY DISTRICT HEALTH DEPARTMENT AND CHARLES WELCH, WASTE WATER CONTROL INSPECTOR.  CHARLES INSPECTED THE STORM DRAIN CLOSE TO THE SPILL AREA AND VERIFIED THAT NO PETROLEUM HAD ENTERRED THE STORM SYSTEM.  THE CLEAN UP CONCLUDED AT 23:30.  I ASKED CAPT. FLOCK TO DO A SAFETY INSPECTION BEFORE OPENING THE AREA TO THE PUBLIC.  THE SPILL WAS CAUSED BY THE UST NOT VENTING, BUILDING UP PRESSURE, AND PUSHING PRODUCT BACK UP THROUGH THE FILL AREA.  THIS PROBLEM WAS REPAIRED BY WESTERN ENERGETIX ON THURSDAY MORNING, APRIL 7, 1994.

LERCH REPLACED GASKET WITH 1/2 INCH GORE-TEX SEALANT WHICH SECURED CAR.  A MECHNICAL INSPECTION WAS CONDUCTED BY CAR DEPT., NO EXCEPTIONS NOTED.  AT 1800 HRS CAR WAS RELEASED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

column168: ROUTINE INSPECTION OF TANK CAR ON COUNCIL BLUFFS DEPARTURE TRACK #58 DISCLOSED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  CAR CONTAINED RESIDUE; PREVIOUS REVENUE MOVE WAS ON CNW WAYBILL 48212 OF 3/24, SHIPPED BY ADM CORN SWEETENERS, DECTUAR IL., ORGINATING CEDAR RAPIDS, IA., CONSIGNED CORN SWEETENERS.  INSPECTION DISCLOSED SOURCE OF LEAK WAS THE THREADED AREA OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE, JUST ABOVE THE OUTLET CAP.  LEAK WAS STOPPED COMPLETELY BY TIGHTENING THE OUTLET CAP.  CAR IS EQUIPPED WITH A BOTTOM OPERATED OUTLET VALVE; OPERATING LEVER WAS FOUND FULLY CLOSED, AND SECURED WITH RETAINING PIN.  RATE OF LEAKAGE WAS SUFFICIENTLY SLOW TO ALLOW FOR EVAPORATION OF SPILLAGE PRIOR TO ANY POOLING.  NO CLEANUP FEASIBLE. IOWA DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES WAS NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT, AND ASSIGNED SPILL A NUMBER 04064-RK-1616.  CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED TO ALLOW FOR SHIPPER NOTIFICATION.  WITH RESPECT TO LOOSE OUTLET CAP, MATTER WAS REFERRED TO MR. MARTY RAFFERTY, WILLIAMS PIPE LINE COMPANY, OMAHA.  WITH RESPECT TO THE POSSIBILITY THAT BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS DEFECTIVE AND ALLOWING PRODUCT TO LEAK INTO OUTLET VALVE WAS DEFECTIVE AND ALLOWING PRODUCT TO LEAK INTO OUTLET CAP, MATTER WAS REFERRED TO MR. HOWARD HAYLAND, ADM TRAFFIC, DECTUAR, IL., WHO ADVISED HE WOULD ARRANGE FOR INSPECTION PRIOR TO RE-LOADING OF RAILCAR.

column168: ROUTINE INSPECTION OF RAILCAR ON COUNCIL BLUFFS DEPARTURE TRACK #58 DISCLOSED LEAKING FROM VINCINITY OF BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  AS LEAK APPEARED TO COME FROM TOP VALVE ASSEMBLY, CAR WAS MOVED TO EAST YARD TRACK #1 AND ISOLATED TO ALLOW FOR MORE COMPLETE INSPECTION.  INSPECTION UNDER BLUE FLAG PROTECTION DISCLOSED SOURCE OF LEAK TO BE THE INTERFACE BETWEEN THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE FLANGE; PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM APPROXIMATELY 1/2 THE CIRCUMFERENCE OF THE FLANGE.  THIS ASSEMBLY IS SECURED BY MEANS OF 9/16 INCH ALLEN SCREWS.  ALL ATTEMPTS TO STOP LEAK BY TIGHTENING THESE SCREWS WERE MOST SAFELY COMPLETED BY TRANSFERRING CONTENTS INTO ANOTHER RAILCAR.  WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF THE SHIPPER, EMPTY TANK CAR GATX 29577 WAS LOCATED AT NORTH PLATTE, NEBRASKA, AND DIVERTED TO COUNCIL BLUFFS FOR TRANSFER.  A CONTAINER WAS PLACED TO COLLECT ANY LEAKAGE FROM CAR UTLX 201325 UNTIL TRANSFER COULD BE COMPLETED.  ON 4/11/94, CONTENTS OF CAR UTLX 201325 WERE TRANSFERRED TO CAR GATX 29577 BY WYNNE TRANSPORT COMPANY, OMAHA.  THE LEAKING CAR, UTLX 201325, WAS STENCILED IN ACCORDANCE WITH PROVISIONS OF 49 CFR 174.50, AND CAR DIVERTED TO UNION TANK CAR CO., MUSCATINE, IA., FOR REPAIR. MOVING ON UP W/B 000000 OF 4/11/94, ROUTED MP KC SOO.  CAR GATX 29577 WAS FORWARDED TO DESTINATION, MOVING ON UP WAYBILL 183566 OF 4/11/94.  REPORT WAS FILED WITH THE IOWA DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES, AND SPILL NUMBER 04064-RK-1616 ASSIGNED.  NO CLEANUP WAS NECESSARY AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.

column168: ON APRIL 12, 1994, AT APPROXIMTELY 0540 HOURS, SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEAN WOMACK WAS NOTIFIED THAT TANK CAR UTLX 12743 WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR DURING SWICHING OPERATIONS.  HE WAS ALSO NOTIFIED THAT SWITCHMAN, ROBERT GOINS HAD A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SPLASHED ON HIS HEAD.  WOMACK SPOKE WITH MR. GOINS BY TELEPHONE, AND HE INFORMED WOMACK THAT HE WASHED HIS HAIR AND SCALP WITH SOAP AND WATER.  WOMACK RECOMMENDED THAT HE SEEK MEDICAL TREATMENT.  MR. GOINS WAS TREATED AND RELEASED AT WILLIS-KNIGHTON SOUTH HOSPITAL, SHREVEPORT, LA GOINS STATED THAT HE WAS NOT INJURED BY THIS EXPOSURE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0620 HOURS, WOMACK ARRIVED AT REISOR YARD.  HE INSPECTED THE TANK CAR AND FOUND THE FILL COVER GASKET CRIMPED BY THE FILL COVER.  THE IMPROPERLY APPLIED GASKET CRIMPED BY THE PRODUCT TO PASS OVER AND UNDER THE GASKET.  HE REMOVED THE GASKET AND SECURED THE FILL COVER WITH GORE-TEX SEALANT. THE SMALL AMOUNT OF SPILLAGE ON THE CAR AND GROUND WAS NETRUALIZED BY LIME.

column168: INSPECTION OF RAILCAR DISCLOSED PRODDUCT DRIPPING FROM BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  CAR IS EQUIPPED WITH AN VALVE, WITH A 4-INCH PIPE NIPPLE SERVING AS THE VALVE NOZZLE.  THIS IS SECURED BY MEANS OF A REDUCER AND 3-INCH PLUG.  ALL LEAKAGE WAS STOPPED BY TIGHTENING THE ABOVE PLUG.  CONTACTED MR. FRED ADAMS, TEXASGULF, AND FURNISHED DETAILS OF THIS INCIDENT.  A SLIGHT ACCUMULATION OF PRODUCT WAS FOUND BENEATH RAILCAR, AND WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH BAKING SODA.

column168: INSPECTION DISCLOSED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM BOTTOM OF TANK CAR, IN VINCINITY OF BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  RAILCAR IS EQUIPPED WITH AN INTERNAL VALVE.  THE OPENING IS COVERED WITH A BLIND FLANGE, WITH A TELL-TALE PLUG IN THE CENTER OF THE BLIND FLANGE, WITH A TELL TALE PLUG IS THE CENTER OF THE BLIND FLANGE.  SOURCE OF LEAK WAS DETERMINED TO BE THIS PLUG, AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED COMPLETELY BY TIGHTENING THE PLUG 1/2 TURN.  A SLIGHT ACCUMULATION OF PRODUCT WAS NOTED BENEATH RAILCAR, AND WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH BAKING SODA ONCE LEAK WAS STOPPED.

column168: INSPECTION OF TANK CAR DISCLOSED RUPTURE DISC HAD FAILED IN VENT ASSEMBLY. ONLY SLIGHT PRODUCT LOSS RESULTED, ALL OF WHICH WAS CONTAINED ON TOP OF RAILCAR. column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: ROLL-BY INSPECTION OF RAILCAR DISCLOSED PRODUCT VISIBLE ON SIDES OF TANK, INDICATING A POSSIBLE LEAK FROM TOP OF CAR.  SUBSEQUENT INSPECTION DISCLOSED SOURCE OF LEAK WAS THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY. RAILCAR WAS EQUIPPED WITH A GATX 261-53 VENT HOUSING AND FDI DISC (100#).  A SMALL BUT VISIBLE CRACK WAS NOTED AT THE TOP OF THE HOUSING, WITH THE ACTUAL CAUSE OF LEAKAGE FOUND TO BE A FAILED RUPTURE DISC.  AS AN FDI DISC WAS NOT IMMEDIATELY AVAILABLE, A CDC DISC OF EQUAL RATING WAS INSTALLED, AND CAR RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.  MR. FRED ADAMS, TEXASGULF, WAS FURNISHED DETAILS OF THIS INCIDENT, AND AUTHORIZED USE OF THE CDC DIC.  A SLIGHT ACCUMULATION OF PRODUCT WAS NOTED ON THE GROUND ON BOTH SIDES OF THE RAILCAR, AND WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH BAKING SODA.  NO CLEANING OF THE SIDES OR TOP OF THE RAILCAR WAS FEASIBLE DUE TO HEAVY RAINS WHICH STRUCK THE AREA TOWARD THE COMPLETION OF REPAIRS.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1730 HRS MR. HARRY W RODABOUGH THE MGR OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION AT SALT LAKE CITY, UT WAS NOTIFIED THAT SWITCH CREW, WHILE SWITCHING THE YARD, ATTEMPTED TO COUPLE TO TANKCAR AMOX 33841 AND AS THEY MADE THE JOINT, THE CAR VENT, MAKING A LOUD NOISE.  THERE WAS A VISIBLE PLUME OF GAS THAT ERRUPTED FROM THE CAR.  THIS QUICKLY DISSPATED AND THE CAR APPEARED TO BE OK AT THE TIME OF HIS POSITION IN THE TOWER. HE STATED THAT THE CAR WAS HANDLED IN THE PROPER MANNER. THE CAR WAS INSPECTED BY MR. RODABOUGH AT 1759 HOURS AND THE SAFETY VALVE ASSEMBLY WAS STILL ICED UP AND LEAKING.  THE LEAK APPEARED TO BE MINOR, BUT FAILED TO RESPOND TO ANY ATTEMPT AT REPAIR.  INFORMATION ON THE CAR INDICATED THAT IT HAD RECENTLY MOVED FROM AMOCO OIL, ON A SWITCH MOVE FROM AMOCO IN ROUTE IT DRGW RR. MR. RODABOUGH CALLED AMOCO OIL, TALKING WITH MR. STEVE DUVALL, SUPERVISOR MAINTENANCE AND SERVICE AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE THE CAR MOVED BACK TO THE LOAD RACK FOR TRANSFER.  IN COMPANY WITH MR. DUVAL THE CAR WAS AGAIN INSPECTED PRIOR TO MOVE AND WAS STILL LEAKING.  SWITCH CREW USING 5 BUFFER CARS MADE THE MOVE AT 2045 HRS.  TRANSFER OF PRODUCT WAS COMPLETED, USING ALL AMOCO PERSONNEL, ON 041594 AT 1100 HRS.  EMPTY CAR WILL BE MOVED TO REPAIR FACILITY.

DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY JOHN SCHNEIDER, CORRIDOR MANAGER, HARRIMAN DISPATCH CENTER, OMAHA, THAT THE YERMO YARD REPORTED A TANK CAR LEAKING. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED GARY HUTNER, MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, WHO STATED TANK CAR JRSX 785027 WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM TOP PORTION OF THE CAR DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS. THE CAR WAS SET TO THE WEST END OF THE RIP TRACK (TRACK 21) AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. THIS CAR ARRIVED YERMO IN THE HKYR-11 AT 0433 HOURS, THURSDAY, APRIL 14, 1994. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BURST RUPTURE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT. THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD MIDLAND BAFFLE, WAS DISASSEMBLED AFTER REMOVING SEAL UPC 421975 FROM THE PROTECTIVE COVER PORT/KEEPER PIN. THE RUPTURE DISC WAS REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE 100 POUND STAINLESS/ TEFLON BS&B RUPTURE DISC. THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE ALSO INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASE FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION. DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SPILLED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE NOT MADE TO THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES, OR TO THE COUNTY OF SAN BERNARDINO DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: NORTH LITTLE ROCK MYO CROW CONTACTED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPECIAL AGENT CARMAN ADVISING THAT A YARD SWITHMAN REPORTED AN ODOR IN BOWL TRACK 12 AND BELIEVES IT TO BE COMING FROM A TANKCAR. HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPECIAL AGENT CARMAN RESPONDED AND LOCATED THE ODOR COMING FROM TANKCAR GATX 92193, A RESIDUE TANKCAR OF BUTANOLS. UPON INSPECTING THE TANKCAR CARMAN DETERMINED THE VAPORS COMING FROM THE MANWAY COVER. INSPECTION REVEALED A WASHER HAD SLIPPED BETWEEN THE MANWAY COVER AND HOUSING PREVENTING PROPER SECUREMENT. TWO OF THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE ALSO LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT. CARMAN REPOSITIONED THE WASHER IN IT'S PROPER PLACE AND RE-SECURED THE MANWAY COVER, STOPPING THE VAPORS FROM LEAVING THE TANK. IT APPEARS THE WASHER HAD FALLEN DOWN AFTER THE CAR WAS UNLOADED. JAMES JACKSON OF TEXAS EASTMAN WAS NOTIFIED ABOUT THE INCIDENT.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: PACKAGE WAS PART OF AN INBOUND FREIGHT LOAD TO THE MEMPHIS HUB/AIR OPERATIONS FACILITY. THIS WAS PART OF A SHIPMENT LOADED ON FLIGHT #289, TAIL #213FE FROM ELP-LLB-MEM. CREW WAS 20 MINUTES OUTISIDE OF MEMPHIS WHEN THEY NOTICED STRONG GASOLINE TYPE ODORS FILTERING IN THE COCK PIT AREA. THEY RADIOED INTO MEMPHIS THAT THEY WERE EXPERIENCING FUMES PROBLEMS AND REQUESTED THAT A DG RESPONSE TEAM MEET THE AIRCRAFT UPON ARRIVAL. THE AIRCRAFT WAS UNLOADED AND THE SHIPMEMT CAUSING THE PROBLEM WAS LOCATED AND ISOLATED. THE PACKAGE WAS OPENED UP TO REVEAL TOPS MISSING FROM 4 OF THE 19 CAN IN THE BOX. THERE WERE STRONG ODORS COMING FROM THE REST OF THE CANS AS WELL. THE CONTAINER WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND IS BEING HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION OF THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column58: Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: (A & B) AT 0203 A.M. ON 04/15/94, SORT SUPERVISOR, GARY LEE REPORTED A SPILL IN BUILDING "C" EXCEPTION AREA OF OUR SORT HUB FACILITY LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  THE SPILL WAS REPORTED AS SEVERAL PACKAGES WERE LEAKING A CLEAR LIQUID WITH A "STRANGE ODOR", WITH ONE PERSON IN CONTACT.  HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS, ALAN HENDERSON AND JIM GILLIAM RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL, TECHNICIANS HENDERSON AND JIM GILLIAM DONNED CARTRIDGE MASKS AND APPROACHED THE TWO PACKAGE IN QUESTION.  BOTH FIBERBOARD BOXES HAD WET SPOTS ON OR NEAR ONE CORNER AND AT THAT TIME TOOK A PH READING AND HAD A POSITIVE READING OF "O TO 1", WHICH INDICATES THAT WHATEVER THE CONTENTS IN THE PACKAGE WAS THAT WAS LEAKING WAS AN "ACID". THE TECHNICIANS AT THIS TIME OPENED ONE OF THE PACKAGES IN QUESTION AND FOUND A LAWN MOWER BATTERY WHICH APPEARED TO HAVE LEAKED FROM THE FILLING CAPS.  ANOTHER PH READING WAS TAKEN AND THE RESULTS WERE A POSITIVE ACID READING OF "0 TO 1".  THE OTHER ITEMS IN THE PACKAGE WERE NON-HAZARDOUS MISCELLANEOUS ITEMS SUCH AS SPARK PLUGS, FILTERS, MOWER BLADES, BELTS, AND MOTOR OIL FOR LAWN MOWERS.  THE OTHER PACKAGE IN QUESTION ALSO CONTAINED A LAWN MOWER BATTERY WHICH ALSO LEAKED FROM THE FILLER CAPS AND THE SAME TYPE OF NON-HAZARDOUS MISCELLANEOUS ITEMS.  THE DIMS OF BOTH PACKAGES ARE APPROXIMATELY 13" H X22 1/2" W X 34" LONG.  NEITHER OF THE PACKAGES WERE MARKED OR LABELED IN ANY MANNER TO WARN ANYONE THAT THE PACKAGES WERE MARKED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  AT THAT TIME, BOTH BATTERIES WERE PLACED IN PLASTIC BAGS AND EACH WERE PLACED BACK IN THEIR RESPECTIVE PACKAGES.  THE TECHNICIANS THEN CONTACTED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR, TONY FRYE, BY RADIO TO COME AND ASSIST IN NEUTRALIZING THE SPILLED BATTERY ACID AND DECONTAMINATING ANY OTHER PROPERTY THAT MAY HAVE BEEN LEAKED ON.  THE TECHNICIANS CLEARED THE AREA AT 0257 A.M. AND THE PACKAGES WERE TAKEN TO THE HAZ MAT SORT FACIITY WHERE BOTH PACKAGES WERE PLACED UNDER LOCK AND KEY.  THE PERSON IN CONTACT WAS P/T SORTER, JIM HAMBY.  THE POINT OF CONTACT ON JIM HAMBY WAS HIS HANDS, AND AS STANDARD PROCEDURE, HE WENT AND WASHED HIS HANDS WITH LIQUID SOAP AND WARM WATER.  JIM HAMBY DID NOT SUSTAIN ANY INJURIES DUE TO THE SPILL, NOR DID HE MISS ANY WORK, THUS THERE WERE NO CLAIMS FILED IN HIS BEHALF.  HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR, BEN TAYLOR, IS FILING THIS REPORT ON BEHALF OF P/T SPILL TECHNICIANS ALAN HENDERSON AND JIM GILLIAM. THE ABOVE STATEMENT, TO MY KNOWLEDGE, IS TRUE AND ACCURATE BASED ON THE INFORMATION AND FACTS GIVEN TO ME.

column42: ACETIC ACID SOLUTION, NOT LESS THAN 50 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 80 PERCENT ACID, BY MASS
column168: ON 04/19/94 AT APPROXIMATELY 0258 HRS, I, KAREN NICHOLS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR OF ABX AIR, INC.  145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177 INVESTIGATED A LEAKING SHIPMENT IN OUR SORT FACILITY AT THE SAME ADDRESS.  THE SHIPMENT WAS EMITTING AN ODOR OF VINEGAR AND THE OUTER FIBREBOARD BOX WAS SATURATED WITH THE LEAKING MATERIAL.  THE FIBREBOARD BOX WAS LABELED WITH AN EXCEPTED QUANTITY LABEL FOR CLASS 8 UN2582, UN1814, AND UN2790.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION WE FOUND 1 X 30 ML GLASS VIAL BROKEN.  THIS VIAL AND 1 OTHER 30 ML VIAL CONTAINED 99.2% ACETIC ACID SOLUTION/0.8% SULFANILIC ACID; 2 X 30 ML GLASS VIALS 10% FERRIC  CHLORIDE; 2 X 30 ML GLASS VIALS OF 40% POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE; AND 2X 30 ML GLASS VIALS 5% N, N-DIMETHYL-ALPHA NAPHTHYLAMINE.  THE LEAKING SPILLING OUT OF THE CONFINES OF THE FIBREBOARD BOX BUT THE FIBREBOARD BOX WAS VERY WET.  THE SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED IN A D.O.T. APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED ON TO ITS DESTINATION.

ON 4-26-94 AT APPROX. 0137 HRS., I, KAREN NICHOLS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR OF ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177, INVESTIGATED A LEAKING SHIPMENT IN OUR SORT FACILITY AT THE SAME ADDRESS. THE LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS BROUGHT TO MY ATTENTION BY JEFF PAYTON/SORT SUPERVISOR. THE SHIPMENT WAS PACKAGED IN A FIBERBOARD BOX WHICH HAD NO HAZARD OR HANDLING LABELS AFFIXED, NOR DID IT HAVE A SHIPPER'S CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ACCOMPANYING IT. INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX I FOUND AN EXTINGUISHER TYPE METAL SPRAY BOTTLE THAT HAD LEAKED DUE TO THE SAFETY PIN BEING DISLODGED DURING TRANSPORT. THE CHEMICAL THAT LEAKED WAS A FORMALDEHYDE NEUTRALIZER. AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF THE LIQUID LEAKED. THE ORINGINAL PRESSURE OF THE SPRAY BOTTLE IS UNDETERMINABLE. THE SHIPMENT IS HELD IN OUR HAZ MAT SECURITY AREA PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.

THIS SHIPMEMT WILL BE HELD PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: 05:00 SARNIA DRIVER DAVID CAREY LEFT SARNIA TERMINAL WITH 6235 IMP. GALLONS OF TOLUENE 3.2 (9.2) UN 1294 II - DRIVER ROUTED 290 S THRUWAY TO EXIT AT I90 EASTBOUND THRUWAY NEAR WILLIAMSVILLE, N.Y. - EXIT RAMP FROM 290 TO 90 IS A LONG GENTLE CURVE, HIGHWAY SPEED OF 55 MPH - THE EXIT OFF RAMP (290 TO 90) MERGES INTO TWO (2) LANES OF A FOUR (4) LANE 90 - 3RD PARTY VEHICLE WAS TRAVELLING IN CURB LANE OF 90 - TANK TRUCK DRIVER (IT WOULD SEEM) LOST CONTROL OF VEHICLE ON EXIT RAMP - TRACTOR/TRAILER MADE CONTACT WITH 3RD PARTY VEHICLE AT BOTTOM OF EXIT RAMP ON 90 THURWAY - THE IMPACT RESULTED IN THE 3RD PARTY VEHICLE MAKING A 180 DEGREE MANUVERE, TRACTOR TRAILER ROLLING OVER (COUNTER CLOCK WISE) TO THE LEFT ONTO 3RD PARTY VEHICLE, PINNING 3RD PARTY VEHICLE AGAINST MEDIAN GUARDRAIL - 10:15 SARNIA TERMINAL, COLIN SHONE, ASSISTANT TERMINAL MANAGER RECEIVED A CALL FROM N.Y. THRUWAY SUPERVISOR DAVE FITZPATRICK (716)863-0868 (CELLULAR) OF THE OCCURRENCE - 10:18 COLIN SHONE CONTACTED PROVOST'S KEASBEY, NEW JERSEY TERMINAL CHUCK GAINES FOR ASSISTANCE. MARK WISMER, OPERATIONS MANAGER, KEASBEY ATTEMPTED TO CONTACT DAVE FITZPATRICK UNSUCCESSFULLY - 10:30 MARK WISMER CALLED CHEMTREC. JEFF SAID N.Y. STATE POLICE HAD ALREADY CALLED IN OCCURENCE. JEFF INDICATED HE WOULD CALL SHIPPER SUN COMPANY INC., AS HE DID NOT HAVE SPECIFIC RESPONSE PROCEDURES. - 10:45 DAVE FITZPATRICK CALLED KEASBEY TERMINAL. MARK WISMER TOLD HIM PROVOST WAS MAKING ARRANGEMENTS WITH TRANSPORT COMPANY CHEMICAL LEAMAN OF TONAWANDA N.Y. FOR POSSIBLE ASSISTANCE IN THE TRANSFER OF THE PRODUCT. CHEMICAL LEAMAN'S ETA 12:30. MARK WISMER THEN WAS TRANSFERRED TO ROBERT CROSSEN OF THE NEW YORK STATE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION AND WAS INFORMED THAT PROVOST TRACTOR/TRAILER WAS IN THE MEDIAN ON A THRUWAY IN AN AREA OF DENSE POPULATION AND SIX LANES OF TRAFFIC IN BOTH DIRECTIONS WERE STOPPED AND LOCAL AUTHORITIES HAD IMPLEMENTED A FULL INCIDENT COMMAND RESPONSE. THERE WAS MINOR LEAKAGE, LESS THAN 10 GPM AND CLEAN UP PERSONNEL WITH VACUUM UNITS WERE ENROUTE. IT WAS INDICATED THAT INCIDENT COMMANDER WAS STARTING AN EVACUATION. - 13:10 TWO (2) CHEMICAL LEAMAN DRIVERS ON SITE, ONE HOUSE EVACUATED, PRODUCT DRIPPING AT REAR CLEAN OUT CAP.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 2030 HRS. ON 041994, THE SWITCH CREW SERVICING THE INDUSTRIES, WORKING IN THE SIDING AT ICI EXPLOSIVES AT GOLCONDA NV. MOVED CAR NAHX488546 TO MAKE ROOM FOR TWO LOADS, IN DOING SO THEY FAILED TO RECOGNIZE THAT CAR NAHX488546 WAS STILL IN THE LOADING MODE, RESULTING IN A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 500 LBS. OF AMMONIUN NITRATE, SPREAD OVER TWO RAIL LENGTHS. ON THE MORNING OF THE 20TH. MR. ED ROSS, PLANT MANAGER AT GOLCONDA OBSERVED THE SPILL AND IMMEDIATELY ORGANIZED A CREW AND WENT TO WORK, TO CLEANUP THE SPILLED PRODUCT AS INCLEMENT WEATHER WAS IN THE FORECAST IN THE NEXT 24HRS. HE REPORTS THAT THEY WERE ABLE TO RECOVER 95% OF THE PRODUCT, WITH THE USE OF A WET DRY SHOP VAC AND SHOVELS AND BROOM, THE PROCESS TAKING OVER 12 HRS. THERE WILL BE NO DISPOSAL PROBLEM AS THEY WERE ABLE TO SCREEN THE SPILLED PRODUCT AND PUT IT BACK IN THE SYSTEM.  A POTENTIAL CLAIM FOR MAN HOURS AND EQUIPMENT AND DELAY IN PLANT OPERATION. MR. RODABOUGH ARRANGED WITH CLAIMS DEPT. AT PALESTINE TO CONTACT ICI EXPLOSIVE AT WINNEMUCCA AND MAKE THE NECESSARY FORMS AND INFORMATION AVAILABLE TO RECOVER THEIR LOSSES. MR. RODABOUGH FILED ALL NECESSARY REPORTS WITH STATE OF NEVADA INCLUDING EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT (MR. FRANK COADY) WHO ASSIGNED INCIDENT #H940428A. A REPORT WAS ALSO FILED WITH NEVADA DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION.

column168: 3:45 PM ERI RECEIVED INITIAL CALL TO RESPOND FROM MR. LEONARD LEACH OF CWX.  THE HAZAROUS MATERIAL RELEASED IN A CWX TRAILER WAS BELIEVED TO BE METHYL ZIRAM (ZINC DIMETHYLDITHICARBAMATE) AN AGRICULTURAL FUNGICIDE.  ERI REQUESTED COPIES OF THE MSDS FOR THE PRODUCT TO BE AVAILABLE WHEN THEIR RESPONSE ACTION TEAM ARRIVED ON SITE.  METHYL ZIRAM IS LISTED AS A CLASS B POISON.  ERI ASSURED MR. LEACH THE TEAM WOULD BE ON SITE WITHIN 1.5 HOURS. 4:45PM MR. JIM MOTTS, PROJECT MANAGER FOR FRI ARRIVES AT THE CWX FACILITY, AND MEETS WITH MR. LEACH.  MR. MOOTS IS GIVEN COPIES OF THE MSDS AND SHIPPING PAPERS TO REVIEW FOR LISTED HAZARDS AND QUANTITIES OF MATERIAL ON THE TRAILER.  IT IS CURRENTLY UNKNOWN AT THIS TIME AS TO THE EXACT QUANTITY OF MATERIAL RELEASED IN THE TRAILER.  5:15 PM THE ERI RESPONSE ACTION TEAM ARRIVES ON SITE AND IS DIRECTED TO TRAILER NUMBER 7011 AT THE REAR OF THE PROPERTY.  THE TRAILER HAS BEEN SEALED AND ISOLATED SINCE THE DISCOVERY OF THE RELEASED MATERIAL. 5:35 PM TAILGATE SAFETY MEETING IS PERFORMED ADDRESSING ANTICIPATED HAZARDS OF THE CLEANUP, AND INITIAL ENTRY TO VERIFY THAT IT IS THE METHYL ZIRAM THAT HAS BEEN RELEASED, AND TO DETERMINE QUANTITIES AND CLEANUP PROCEDURES.  WORK ZONES ARE ALSO ESTABLISHED AT THIS TIME.  IT IS DETERMINED THAT ALL ENTRY AND CLEANUP PROCEDURES WILL REQUIRE LEVEL C PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT (PPE). INITIAL ENTRY BEGINS.  6:00 DURING THE INITIAL ENTRY ERI OBSERVED AT LEAST TWO LEAKING BAGS OF THE METHYL ZIRAM AND APPROXIMATELY 8 TO 10 POUNDS OF THE MATERIAL ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  A HEPA EQUIPPED VACUUM IS UTILIZED TO REMOVE AND CONTAIN THE MATERIAL SO THAT A FORKLIFT CAN BE USED TO OFF LOAD THE PALLETS FOR RE-STACKING AND REMOVAL OF THE LEAKING BAGS. AFTER CLOSE INSPECTION OF THE LEAKING BAGS IT IS FOUND THAT THE BAGS WHICH ARE LEAKING ARE ON THE SECOND AND THIRD ROWS OF THE PALLET AND HAVE ROUND HOLES IN THE BAGS.  THE HOLES IN THE BAGS ARE NOT THE SIZE AND SHAPE OF HOLES THAT WOULD BE GENERALLY ASSOCIATED WITH FORKLIFT DAMAGE. 6:10 PM BREAK  6:20 PM RE-ENTRY TO OFFLOAD PALLETS AND REMOVE THE LEAKING BAGS. PALLET ONE IS OFF LOADED RE-STACKED AND TWO LEAKING BAGS PLACED IN PLY BAGS TO CONTAIN THE LEAKS, THE RE-PACKAGED BAGS WERE PLACED ON TOP OF THE PALLET.  THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER IS CLEANED OF REMAINING VISIBLE PRODUCT. 6:55 PM CWX IS REQUESTED TO MOVE THE TRAILER TO THEIR DOCK AREA TO OFFLOAD THE REMAINING PALLETS FOR FURTHER INSPECTION AND CLEANING OF THE TRAILER. 7:25 PM THE TRAILER IS MOVED TO THE LOADING DOCK AREA AND THE PALLETS REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER.  DURING THE OFF-LOADING OF THE FOURTH PALLET ANOTHER SPILL OF ZIRAM IS ENCOUNTERED THIS SPILL MEASURES APPROXIMATELY 3' X 4' X 1" IN SIZE.  THE SOURCE FOR THIS MATERIAL SPILL IS UNKNOWN AT THIS TIME AS NO BAGS ON THIS PALLET ARE LEAKING.  THE SPILL AREA IS CLEANED UP AND PALLET REMOVAL CONTINUES.  7:35 PM THE FIFTH PALLET IS BEING IS OFF-LOADED AND MORE MATERIAL IS FOUND UNDER THE PALLET NO LEAKING BAGS ARE OBSERVED ON THIS PALLET.

JEFFREY A. HUNT, A BADGER FEDERAL SERVICES, INC. SEMI-DRIVER SUCCESSFULLY AVOIDED A COLLISION WITH AN AUTOMOBILE THAT CONTINUED ON WITHOUT STOPPING. HOWEVER, THE RESULT WAS A SHIFT IN THE FREIGHT THAT WAS IN THE TRAILER. JEFF INSPECTED THE FREIGHT.  UPON INITIAL INVESTIGATION IT APPEARED SOMETHING  WAS DRIPPING ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE AREA WAS SECURED AND A PHONE CALL TO BADGER FEDERAL SERVICES, INC. WAS MADE.  BADGER FEDERAL SERVICES, INC. IN TURN CONTINUED WITH PROPER NOTIFICATION OF THE INCIDENT. THE LOAD SHIFT CAUSED A PUNCTURE IN TWO (2) DRUMS OF #4304 ISOSET 5% SOLUTION CUMENE HYDROPEROXIDE SHIPPED BY ASHLAND CHEMICAL.  RIEDEL CHEMICAL, WORKING FOR ASHLAND CHEMICAL COMPANY, OVERPACKED THE AFFECTED ITEMS AND SHIPPED THEM BACK TO ASHLAND CHEMICAL COMPANY INCLUDING THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL USED TO CONTAIN THE SPILL.  THE TRAILER AFFECTED WAS CLEANED OUT AT THE SCENE BY WARNER & SONS OF ELKHART, INDIANA.  THE METHOD USED WAS TO PRESSURE WASH AND RINSE THREE (3) TIMES.  THE RESULTING LIQUID WAS RECOVERED AND DISPOSED OF BY SER OIL COMPANY OF MISHAWAKA, INDIANA THRU THEIR WASTE WATER TREATMENT PLANT.  BADGER FEDERAL SERVICES, INC.  IS NO LONGER ACCEPTING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TRUCK LOAD SHIPMENTS.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, LOW SPECIFIC ACTIVITY (LSA-I) NON FISSILE OR FISSILE-EXCEPTED
column168: BACKGROUND: ON TUESDAY, APRIL 19, 1994, SEQUOYAH FUELS CORPORATION (SFC) SHIPPED THREE (3) SHIPMENTS OF URANIUM ORE CONCENTRATE (YELLOWCAKE) FROM IT'S FACILITY AT GORE, OKLAHOMA TO THE ALLIED SUGNAL, INC. FACILITY AT METROPOLIS, IL. THE SHIPMENTS WERE VIA SEMI-TRAILER TRUCK AND THE CARRIER WAS TRI-STATE MOTOR TRANSIT COMPANY. THE SHIPMENTS WERE RELEASED FROM THE SFC SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 1000, AND WERE TRAVELLING TOGETHER EN ROUTE TO THEIR DESTINATION. NOTIFICATION OF EVENT: AT APPROXIMATELY 1700 SFC RECEIVED NOTIFICATION OF THE EVENT FROM THE TRI-STATE DISPATCHER. IT WAS STATED THAT THE DRIVER IN THE TRUCK BEHIND THE VEHICLE INVOLVED HAD NOTED AN APPARENT WATER LEAK FROM INSIDE THE TRAILER. THE OBSERVED WATER OUTSIDE THE TRAILER WAS OBSERVED TO BE ON A MUD FLAP AND APPROXIMATELY 1 SQUARE FOOT ON THE HIGHWAY SURFACE. ON INSTRUCTIONS FROM SFC, THE DRIVER BROKE THE SEAL ON THE TRUCK AND LOOKED IN THE TRAILER. UPON OPENING THE TRAILER, A WET SPOT (NO STANDING WATER) COVERING APPROXIMATELY 10 SQUARE FEET WAS OBSERVED. THE WATER APPEARED TO BE COMING FROM A SINGLE DRUM IN THE SECOND ROW FROM THE BACK OF THE TRAILER. THE TRUCKS WERE JUST EAST OF FORREST CITY, ARKANSAS ON US INTERSTATE 40 AT MILE MARKER 242 AT THE TIME. THIS IS APPROXIMATELY SIX (6) HOURS FROM THE SEQUOYAH FUELS CORPORATION FACILITY. BASED ON THE INFORMATION AVAILABLE, THE PRELIMINARY RESPONSE INCLUDED THE ASSESSMENT THAT NO EVENT CLASSIFICATION WAS REQUIRED UNDER THE PROVISIONS OF THE SEQUOYAH FUELS CORPORATION CONTINGENCY PLAN, NOTIFICATION TO THE DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION (DOT) WAS REQUIRED, AND A COURTESY CALL SHOULD BE MADE TO THE NRC NOTIFYING THEM OF THE EVENT. THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED AT 1800, REPORT NO. 235633, AND THE NRC OPERATIONS CENTER WAS NOTIFIED AT 1820, REPORT NO. 27124. PREPARATIONS WERE MADE TO DISPATCH A RESPONSE AND ASSESSMENT TEAM TO THE EVENT SITE TO ASSESS AND REMEDIATE THE LEAK. THE PREPARATIONS INCLUDED A REVIEW OF THE MATERIALS AVAILABLE IN THE RESPONSE TRAILER AND THE ADDITION OF OTHER ITEMS WHICH MIGHT BE NEEDED, INCLUDING A DRUM LIFTING DEVICE, DRYING AGENT (CEMENT), OVERPACK DRUMS, AND A DRUM DOLLY. THE RESPONSE TEAM LEFT THE SFC SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 1930. THE RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED AT THE EVENT SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 0115 ON APRIL 20. IN ADDITION TO THE TRUCK DRIVERS, TWO REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE ARKANSAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH PATROL ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 0245. THE SURVEY OF THE AREA, BOTH INSIDE AND OUTSIDE THE VEHICLE AND ON THE ROADWAY BENEATH THE VEHICLE, INDICATED THAT THERE WAS NO REMOVABLE CONTAMINATION ABOVE APPLICABLE NRC RELEASE LIMITS. A DIRECT RADIATION SURVEY WAS ALSO PERFORMED AND CONFIRMED THAT THERE WAS NO CONTAMINATION ABOVE THE RELEASE LIMITS. THE TRUCK CONTENTS WERE INSPECTED AND THE SUSPECT DRUM WAS ISOLATED. WHEN THE DRUM WAS TILTED TO MOVE IT, A SMALL AMOUNT OF WATER "SLOSHED" OUT, APPARENTLY BYPASSING THE GASKET. NO FAILURE OF THE DRUM LID OR CLOSURE RING WAS APPARENT. WHEN THE LID WAS REMOVED, IT WAS NOTED TH

column168: SUPERVISOR RUSS YEALEY RECIEVED A CALL AT THE CENTER FROM THE DRIVER ON ROAD.  HE STATED HE HAD A PACKAGE TIPPED OVER AND THE CORNER WAS WET.  HE STATED THAT HE SAT THE PACKAGE UPRIGHT, SECURED THE VEHICLE AND CALLED. RUSS ASKED DAVE IF HE KNEW THE NAME OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INVOLVED AND HE DID, HE INFORMED RUSS THAT IT WAS AMMONIA HYDROXIDE AND HE ALSO GAVE RUSS THE 800 TELEPHONE NUMBER THAT THE SHIPPER GAVE HIM IN CASE HE EVER HAD A PROBLEM.  AFTER REVIEWING THE HAZARDOUS RESPONSE GUIDE AND SPEAKING WITH PROFESSIONAL RESPONDER #8 RUSS FELT THAT THE DRIVER WAS IN NO IMMEDIATE DANGER.  THE DRIVER WAS LESS THAN ONE MILE FROM THE SHIPPER AND RUSS INSTRUCTED DRIVER TO CLOSE BULKHEAD AND LEAVE CAB DOORS OPEN AND RETURN PACKAGE TO SHIPPER.  PROFESSIONAL RESPONDER #8 1-800-535-5053 AMMONIA HYDROXIDE (2672).

PART TIME SUPERVISOR, JERRY THOMAS, CAME TO THE RESPONDER, GARY BALL, SAYING THERE WAS A LEAKING PACKAGE.  GARY FOLLOWED THE RECOMMENDATIONS ON PAGE 26 OF EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK FOR TAKING UP MATERIAL AND CONTAINING.  DAMAGED PACKAGE AND ABSORBANT TAKEN AND DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PROCEDURE.

DRIVER, RON SCHUELLER, CONTACTED CENTER.  RESPONDER, PEGGY VOGELSANG, MET DRIVER ON ROUTE.  PACKAGE WAS P/U AND RETURNED TO CENTER.  PACKAGE DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.  DRIVER WAS NOT AWARE OF THE DAMAGED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL UNTIL SEVERAL MINUTES AFTER CONTACT WITH THE PACKAGE.  HE WASHED HIS HANDS, BUT AS HE CONTINUED ON HIS ROUTE HIS HANDS BEGAN TO BLISTER.  HE WENT TO THE HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT AND WAS RELEASED TO WORK.  THE DRIVER RETURNED TO WORK THE NEXT DAY AND ROAD WITH A SUPERVISOR FOR OBSERVATION.  THE DRIVER WAS BACK ON 4/27/94 WITH NO PROBLEMS.

AT 03:00 A CALL ABOUT A LIQUID DAMAGE IN MINEOLA, WAS MADE TO THE DMP AREA.  J. PARRINO RESPONDED TO THE CALL WITH THE SPILL CART.  THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A SPILL TUB AND BROUGHT TO THE DMP AREA.  THE LEAKAGE WAS ABSORBED BY THE OUTSIDE CARTON, THE AREA WAS CLEANED WITH SPEEDI-DRI AND SOLUSORB.  THE CONTAMINATED PORTION OF THE DAMAGE WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE S.C.B.A. WAS NOT USED BECAUSE THERE WERE NO FUMES OR ODORS PRESENT. NO INJURIES OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF THIS DAMAGE.  INFORMATION ABOUT THIS DAMAGE FORWARDED TO SORT MANAGER FOR REVIEW.

ON 4/8/94 SORT SUPERVISOR, KERRY BARKER REPORTED A SHIPMENT OUTSIDE THE MAIN SORT WAS EMITTING A HISSING SOUND. UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE, I, MICHAEL A. FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORD., OBSERVED A FIBERBOARD BOX SITTING ON THE RAMP. THERE WAS A SMALL HOLE IN ONE END WITH A METAL PIECE PROTRUDING. I OPENED THE FIRBERBOARD BOX AND FOUND A METAL CYLINDER WHICH HAD A VALVE ON EACH END. THE END WHICH PROTRUDED THRU THE FIBERBOARD BOX, THE VALVE WAS PARTIALLY OPEN. THIS ALLOWED FOR SOME OF THE INNER GAS TO LEAK OUT. MARKED ON THE METAL CYLINDER WAS "RAW GAS ONLY". THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD AND A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED FROM THE SHIPPER. WHEN WE RECEIVED THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET FROM THE SHIPPER, IT SHOWED THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME TO BE "CARBON DIOXIDE, REFRIGERATED LIQUID". THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. THIS SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.
MOTOR CARRIER INSPECTOR NOTICED A FEW DROPS LEAVE VALVE. COMMENTED "INTERNAL VALVE OPEN". THE VALVES WAS CLOSED. UNKNOWN WHY A COUPLED OF DROPS ESCAPED. VALVE WAS CHECKED TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION.

PACKAGES WERE BEING HANDLED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE OCCURED.  THE PACKAGES WERE APPARENTLY DROPPED IN HANDLING.  THE PACKAGES WERE ISOLATED TO REVEAL VARIOUS TYPES PAINT RELATED SUPPLIES (SEE ATTACHED PACKING LIST).  PRINCIPAL OF THESE WERE AEROSOL CANS CLEARLY MARKED AS ADHESIVES.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND AN MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND IS ATTACHED TO THIS REPORT.  THE INFORMATION ON THE MSDS CLEARLY SHOWS THIS ITEM TO BE A FLAMMABLE ITEM.  THERE WERE NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MARKINGS, LABELS, OR SHIPPING CERTIFICATIONS ASSOCIATED WITH THIS SHIPMENT.  THE PACKAGE IS BEING HELD PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.
CONTENTS LEAKED COMING DOWN THE SIDE. PROPER STEPS WERE TAKEN FOR HAZARDOUS CLEAN UP, PACKAGE WAS REBOXED AND SENT TO DESTINATION. SHIPPER NEEDS TO SEAL THE CONTAINER TO PREVENT OPENING.

TUESDAY EVENING, APRIL 26, 1994, PERSONNEL AT THE FEDERAL EXPRESS PHOENIX, ARIZONA RAMP HAD NOTED A SMALL DENT IN ONE OF TWO STEEL DRUMS OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL SHIPPED BY THE NUCLEAR SCIENCE CENTER AT TEXAS A&M UNIVERSITY ON APRIL 25, 1994 TO SPECTRATEK SERVICES, ALBUQUERQUE, NEW MEXICO. BECAUSE OF THE DENT THE DRUM WAS SURVEYED AND IT PRESENTED A 16 TI. THE SHIPPING PAPER (COPY ATTACHED) DESCRIBED THE SHIPMENT: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, N.O.S. 7, UN2982 2 TYPE 7A 30 GAL STEEL DRUMS, ANTIMONY BEADS (SOLID FORM) RADIOACTIVE YELLOW III/III, TI=5.5/7.2 59.2 GBq Sb-122 (1.6 Ci) CARGO AIRCRAFT ONLY  DANGEROUS GOODS ADMINISTRATION REPRESENTATIVE ON CALL WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND HE NOTIFIED DR. ROY PARKER, RADIATION PHYSICS CONSULTANT, AT 8:04 PM CT. DR. PARKER HAD ADDITIONAL RADIATION MEASUREMENTS TAKEN, CONCLUDED THAT THE SMALL DENT, DESCRIBED AS APPROXIMATELY 0.25 INCHES DEEP, WAS NOT A FACTOR, BUT THAT THE 16 TI WAS AUTHENTIC. THE SECOND DRUM MEASURED 6 TI, CLOSELY CORRESPONDING TO THE STATED 5.5 TI. DR. PARKER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, TEXAS A&M UNIVERSITY NUCLEAR SCIENCE AND THE PHOENIX, ARIZONA CASFO PURSUANT TO 49 CFR 175.31. HE INSTRUCTED THE PHOENIX RAMP TO HOLD THE SHIPMENT IN A SUBSEQUENT TRANSFER OF THE SHIPMENT, SINCE THE 16TI DRUM COULD NOT BE FURTHER TRANSPORTED UNLESS IT WAS PERFORMED UNDER EXCLUSIVE USE CONDITIONS. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH SPECTRATEK SERVICES, THE RECIPIENT, TO TAKE DELIVERY OF THE DRUMS AT THE FEDERAL EXPRESS PHOENIX RAMP AND EITHER TRANSPORT THE PACKAGE UNDER EXCLUSIVE USE CONDITIONS, REPACKAGE OR OVERPACK THE DRUM. SPECTRATEK SERVICES TOOK DELIVERY OF THE PACKAGE ON SATURDAY, APRIL 30, TRANSFERRED THE SHIELDED INNER CONTAINER IN THE DRUM TO ANOTHER PACKAGE, AND TRANSPORTED IN THEIR OWN VEHICHLE AS A PRIVATE CARRIER. SPECTRATEK SERVICES REPORTED ON MAY 2, 1994 THAT THEY HAD INSPECTED THE PACKAGE AFTER RECEIPT, MEASURED 13 TI ON THE PACKAGE, AND HAD DETERMINED THAT LEAD SHOT, WHICH PROVIDED ADDITIONAL SHIELDING WITHIN THE CAVITY OF THE SHIELDED INNER CONTAINER HAD APPARENTLY SHIFTED DURING TRANSPORT, THEREBY REDUCING THE SHIELDING IN A GIVEN DIRECTION AND INCREASING THE RADIATION LEVEL AND TI. A COPY OF THE DOT 7A TYPE A PACKAGE DOCUMENTATION REQUIRED TO BE MAINTAINED PURSUANT TO 49 CFR 173415(A) HAD BEEN INITIALLY REQUESTED FROM THE SHIPPER AND WAS SUBSEQUENTLY SUPPLIED BY THE RECIPIENT, SPECTRATEK SERVICES, SINCE IT WAS THEIR PACKAGE. THE ORIGINAL TYPE A PACKAGE DOCUMENTATION DID NOT ADDRESS THE USE OF LEAD SHOT AS ADDITIONAL SHIELDING AND APPARENTLY THIS CONFIGURATION WAS NOT TESTED UNTIL AFTER THIS INCIDENT. THE REVISION DATED MAY 2, 1994 ADDRESSES THE USE OF LEAD SLEEVES AND LEAD SHOT FOR ADDITIONAL SHIELDING, BUT MORE EXPLICIT PACKING INSTRUCTIONS THAN "EXTREME CARE NEEDS TO BE TAKEN TO INSURE THAT CANS CANNOT SHIFT DURING SHIPPING," WOULD SEEM INDICATED. DURING THE INVESTIGATION THE FOLLOWING DISCREPANCIES WERE ALSO NOTED: 1. THE ISOTOPE LISTED ON THE SHIPPING PAPER WAS Sb-122. THE RADIOACTIVE MATE

column168: THE LEAKING PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED ON SOUTH SORT ONE AT 04:38. THE PSC WAS NOTIFIED AND CHERYL COLLINS RESPONDED WITH PPE, A PREPARED SPILL TUB, AND THE GUIDE BOOK. AFTER CONSULTING THE GUIDE BOOK AND DECISION TREE CHERYL CONTAINED THE BOX AND RETURNED TO THE PSC WITH THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. THE DMP WAS STARTED AT 05:06 AND COMPLETED AT 05:36. THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WERE DISPOSED OF UNDER THE HAZARDOUS DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.

RECEIVED A CALL FROM JOE AT 16:45 ABOUT A LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PACKAGE AT THE WILMINGTON CENTER. HE STATED THAT IT WAS A CORROSIVE LIQUID UN1760 CLASS 111. AFTER REVIEWING THE DECISION TREE I RESPONDED TO WILMINGTON WITH GOGGLES, GLOVES APRON AND DMP CART. I REMOVED THE LEAKING PACKAGE FROM THE REAR OF PACKAGE CAR AND PLACED IT IN A SPILL TUB WITH SPEEDY DRY. I PUT SOME SPEEDY DRY ON THE FLOOR OF THE PACKAGE CAR AND RETURNED TO PSC FOR PROCESSING. THE BOX CONTAINED 4 1GALLON CANS OF AMICON ONE OF WHICH WAS PUNCTURED ON THE BOTTOM. PUT IN ANOTHER CONTAINER. PROCESSED WET BOX UNDER DMP.

AT 6:58 WEARING GLOVES, GOGGLES, AND APRON, I RESPONDED TO A CALL FROM MARK KELLEY, SUPERVISOR AT NP, TO PICK UP A DAMAGED PACKAGE ON THE SORT BELT. THE LEAK WAS CONFINED TO THE BOX ITSELF. I BROUGHT THE PACKAGE BACK TO PSC OPENED IT AND FOUND 4 OUT OF 4 PLASTIC GALLON JUGS LEAKING FROM LOOSE CAPS. USING THE DECISION TREE AS A GUIDE, I PROCESSED THE DAMAGE PER HAZ MAT DISPOSAL PROCEDURES. I PUT THE HAZ WASTED IN A DMP BAG ALONG WITH SPEEDY DRY. I WAS DONE BY 8PM.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: DURING ROUTINE SORT OPERATIONS, THE PACKAGE CAME APART. INSIDE WAS A CART WITH A ELECTRIC STORAGE 12V BATTERY ALONG WITH SOME PESTICIDE. ALTHOUGH IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE PESTICIDE WAS NOT A DANGEROUS GOOD THE 12 V BATTERY IS. THERE WAS NOT ANY MARKINGS OR LABELS NOR WAS THERE ANY DOCUMENTATION THAT IDENTIFIED THE CONTENTS AS A DANGEROUS GOOD. THE FAA (ADAM KISTLER) WAS NOTIFIED WHO OPENED UP A INVESTIGATION AS THIS IS CONSIDERED A HIDDEN DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT. THE PACKAGE CONSISTED OF TWO APPROX 2 FOOT SQUARE FIBERBOARD BOXES TAPED ONE ON TOP OF EACH OTHER. THE 12V BATTERY WAS THEN INSIDE THE PACKAGE WITH A CART, SOME PESTICIDE AND SOME TYPE OF SPRAYER. ORIGINALLY, A 5800 REPORT WAS NOT COMPLETED BECAUSE A DANGEROUS GOOD DID NOT LEAK. AT THE FAA'S REQUEST, WE COMPLETED A REPORT FOR THEIR USE IN THE INVESTIGATION.
